    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-09-06T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-09-06T21:00:00-05:00" n="799"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d799">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">825.00 Revolutions/33: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in Chile</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Culbertson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-09-06T22:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 6, 1931—10 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>42. Embassy’s 109, September 6, 12 noon. The sale or transfer of submarines owned
                    by this Government is forbidden by Article 18 of the treaty on the limitation of
                    Naval Armament signed at Washington February 6, 1922.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d799fn1">
                        <ref target="frus1922v01#pg_247">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1922, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 247</ref>.</note> As respects the
                    delivery of war material, this Government is disposed to find means of
                    cooperation, but the Department is handicapped in regard to adequate information
                    as to the supplies available at Panama by the week-end holiday, including Labor
                    Day, and the necessity for thorough consideration. It suggests that no public
                    intimation be given of an approach to us until we are able to reply fully,
                    probably tomorrow. As respects tear gas, our information is that there are no
                    supplies of this commodity in Governmental possession at Panama or elsewhere
                    short of commercial producers in this country. The delivery of munitions of war
                    will in any case be slow and difficult, as shipment of them by commercial
                    aircraft appears to be forbidden by Article 15 of the Convention on Commercial
                    Aviation signed at Habana February 20, 1928,<note n="2" xml:id="d799fn2">
                        <ref target="frus1928v01#pg_585">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, 1928, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p.
                            585</ref>.</note> and shipment by sea is slow and obviously complicated
                    by the Chilean Naval situation.</p>
                <pb facs="1029" n="915" xml:id="pg_915"/>
                <p>You may express the appreciation of this Government of the desires of the Chilean
                    Government to maintain order and stable institutions and to protect American
                    interests in Chile, and also our Government’s keen appreciation of the
                    difficulties with which Chile is confronted.</p>
                <p>Please telegraph immediately specific war material desired by the Chilean
                    Government. Point out the possibility of purchasing more adequate supplies from
                    commercial manufacturers here.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Rogers</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
